aiborne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of <b>Clabburn</b>, possibly a variant of   Cliburn  , but the latter is a northwest English name whereas <b>Clabburn</b> is found mostly in Norfolk and the South East, so it is more probably from a lost place in that part of England, perhaps named with Old English <i>clǣg</i> ‘clay’ + <i>burne</i> ‘spring, stream’.","History: William Claiborne (<i>c.</i> 1600–77) was a founding colonist in VA. His descendant, William Charles Claiborne (1775–1817) was the first governor of LA."],"variants":[{"name":"Claborn","meanings":["English: variant of   Claiborne  ."]},{"name":"Clayborne","meanings":["English: variant of   Claiborne  ."]},{"name":"Clayborn","meanings":["English: variant of   Claiborne  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Cliburn","meanings":["English (Middlesex): habitational name from Cliburn (Westmorland), named from Old English <i>clif</i> ‘slope, bank’ + <i>burna</i> ‘stream’. Alternatively, from the rare Middle English personal name <i>Clibern</i>, of uncertain origin."]},{"name":"Clayburn","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lincolnshire): variant of   Claiborne  ."]}]},{"name":"Nathaniel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of a New Testament name, which is derived from the Greek form of a Hebrew name meaning ‘God has given’ (  compare  Nathan  , which is sometimes taken as a short form of this name). It was borne by one of the less prominent of Christ's apostles (John 1:45; 21:2), who in fact is probably identical with   Bartholomew .  The spelling used in the Authorized Version of the New Testament is  <b>Nathanael</b> , but this is in much less frequent use as a given name in the English-speaking world."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Nathaniel Claiborne was born in 1554, in Westmorland, England, United Kingdom as 